Heavy ion research facility (HIRFL)
A high-purity germanium detector to detect the
gamma spectra. The relative efficiency was about 65%
and energy resolution was 1.90 keV at 1.33 MeV. The
absolute efficiency was calibrated with the standard
sources Co-60, Ba-133, Cs-137, and Eu-152.
An air ionization chamber was placed to
monitor the beam current.
Errors concern systematic error,
statistical error, the coincidence summing effect of
gamma transition and inaccuracy of the detector
efficiency.
Heavy ion research facility (HIRFL)
A 250 MeV proton beam bombarded the two
groups of targets. Both irradiations were lasted
about 22 h to get sufficient fluence. After the end
of irradiation, 20 h and 1 h counting times were at
8.1 d and 133.4 d for Cu, 3211 s and 3600 s counting
times were at 4.7 h and 42.5 d for W, and 2811 s and
2811 s counting times were at 7.6 h and 187.4 d for Pb.
With the aid of activity analysis of Al foil, the
ionization chamber was calibrated and the absolute
beam current was obtained.
Two groups of targets: one consisted of W and Cu
foils, another consisted of Pb and Cu foils. The
diameter and thickness of the W and Pb targets were
100 mm and 0.15 mm. The diameter and thickness of the
Cu target were 100 mm and 0.05 mm for both groups. Al
foil with high-purity and 300 um thickness was placed
immediately in front of the ionization chamber.
Data were taked from Tables 2-4 of Journal
of Physics G: Nucl.Part.Phys. 42,125102,2015
